{
  "text": "For a detailed discussion see, for example, [CITATION_1] . In Fig. 2 we show two snapshots of the Wigner function for the oscillator mode -having traced out the qubit (see the on-line animation that accompanies this letter for a movie of the evolution of Wigner function the snapshot shown in Fig. 2 ). Fig. 2(a) is taken very early on in the system evolution at t/2\u03c0 = 0.1. Here we see that the effect of the qubit on the measurement device is to split the coherent state up into two coherent state-like lumps. This is not surprising, as a very similar effect is seen in collapse and revival phenomena of the Jaynes-Cummings model of a qubit interacting with a harmonic oscillator. However, as the system evolves we see in Fig. 2 (b) (t/2\u03c0 = 2.25) the distribution becomes somewhat more interesting. One lump is still quite small and is associated with the qubit's ground state. The second is much larger, arising from the chaotic-like behaviour of the Duffing oscillator and is associated with the qubit's excited state.",
